'''''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down''''' is the fourteenth [[studio album]] by American recording artist [[Ry Cooder]], released August 30, 2011, on [[Nonesuch Records]]. It was written and produced by Cooder and recorded at Drive-By Studios, Ocean Studios, and Wireland Studios in California. Inspired by the [[Late-2000s financial crisis|late-2000s economic crisis]] and past [[protest song]]s, the album features [[topical song]]s about [[political sociology|socio-political]] subject matter in 21st-century America, including politics, war, [[economic inequality|economic disparity]], and social injustice. Its music is rooted in [[Americana (music)|Americana]] and incorporates traditional styles and musical language from historical sources such as [[country blues]], [[tejano music|tejano]], and [[American folk music|American roots music]]. The album has been noted by music writers for its eclectic musical range, allegorical songs, [[working class|working-class]] perspective, and Cooder's sardonic lyrics.

The album's first and only [[single (music)|single]], "Quicksand", was released as a [[music download|digital download]], with the proceeds of its sales subsequently being donated to the [[Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund]]. Although it [[record chart|chart]]ed modestly in the United States, the album attained relatively higher charting in European countries, including Ireland, the United Kingdom, and Norway, where it reached its highest chart position. Upon its release, ''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'' received general acclaim from [[music criticism|music critic]]s, who praised its diverse sound, trenchant commentary, and Cooder's musicianship. Several critics drew comparisons of Cooder to singer-songwriter and folk musician [[Woody Guthrie]]. It was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]], set to be presented at the [[54th Grammy Awards]] in 2012.

== Background and recording ==
The album follows Cooder's 2008 album ''[[I, Flathead]]'' and his work on [[The Chieftains]]' 2010 album ''[[San Patricio (album)|San Patricio]]''.<ref name="Huey">{{cite web|last=Huey|first=Steve|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ry-cooder-p3959/biography|title=Ry Cooder|work=''[[Allmusic]]''|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|at=Biography|year=2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> It was inspired by the [[Late-2000s financial crisis|late-2000s economic crisis]] and past [[protest song]]s.<ref name="Ryssdal">{{cite web|last=Ryssdal|first=Kai|authorlink=Kai Ryssdal|url=http://www.marketplace.org/topics/life/ry-cooder-protest-songs-today?refid=0|title=Ry Cooder on the protest songs of today|work=[[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]]|publisher=[[American Public Media]]|date=August 29, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> In interviews prior to the album's release, Cooder expressed strong anti-Republican and anti-banker sentiments in discussion about the political and economic climate.<ref name="Paton">{{cite web|last=Paton|first=Daniel|url=http://www.musicomh.com/albums/ry-cooder-2_0811.htm|title=Ry Cooder - Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down <nowiki>|</nowiki> album reviews|publisher=[[MusicOMH]]|date=September 5, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> Before conceiving the album, he wrote and recorded the song "Quicksand" in 2010, as a response to the controversy spurred by [[Arizona SB 1070|Arizona Senate Bill 1070]] and anti-[[illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigration]] measure in the United States.<ref name="Quicksand">{{cite web|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/new-ry-cooder-single-quicksand-inspired-by-arizona-immigration-battle-out-on-itunes-june-29-2010-06-24|title=New Ry Cooder Single, "Quicksand," Inspired by Arizona Immigration Battle, Out on iTunes June 29; Proceeds to Benefit MALDEF|publisher=[[Nonesuch Records]]|date=June 24, 2010|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> In an interview for ''[[The Australian]]'', he said of his decision to persue a more political direction with his songwriting, "I was still working on the ''Flathead'' record; that was during [[George W. Bush|<nowiki>[George]</nowiki> Bush]]'s time. I was looking at things and paying attention to events, politically. So I started trying to write political songs because it's good to have something you can do other than just sit and fume about everything. After [[Barack Obama]] got elected I started thinking about other stories that might be good to do. It occurred to me that the social and political problems that we've been having, well [...] it's deja vu all over again, as the man said."<ref name="Shedden">{{cite web|last=Shedden|first=Iain|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/arts/music-and-politics-mix-in-ry-cooders-hands/story-e6frg8n6-1226149071111|title=Music and politics mix in Ry Cooder's hands|work=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|date=October 1, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63nKoMs24|archivedate=2011-12-10}}</ref>

In early 2011, Cooder was inspired to write the song "No Banker Left Behind", and subsequently the rest of the album, by a headline about bankers and other affluent people who had profited from the bank [[bailout]]s and [[late-2000s recession|resulting recession]] during the late-2000s.<ref name="Huey"/> In an interview with [[Kai Ryssdal]] on ''[[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]]'', Cooder cited the song as the starting point for writing the album and stated, "'No Banker Left Behind' originated with a line from [[Robert Scheer]]'s [[Truthdig]] blog. I read this pretty regularly, and when I saw this, this metric I thought 'no banker left behind.'"<ref name="Ryssdal"/> He compared the album's content to [[Woody Guthrie]]'s songs about the [[Dust Bowl]] era during the [[Great Depression in the United States|Great Depression]] and said of his own songs, "What I like in the idea of these songs is if you follow the logic of each tune <U+2014> this happened and this happened and you can see that at the end, this is the result, you just didn't see it this way before, you never thought of [[Wall Street]] in terms of [[Jesse James]] and bilingual heft."<ref name="Ryssdal"/>

Recording sessions for the album took place at Drive-By Studios in North Hollywood, Ocean Studios in Burbank, and Wireland Studios in Chatsworth, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=8565025|title=Ry Cooder - Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down CD Album|publisher=[[CD Universe]], [[Muze]]|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> The album was written and produced entirely by Cooder, except "Lord Tell Me Why", which was co-written by session drummer [[Jim Keltner]].<ref name="liner">{{cite album-notes|title=Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|artist=Ry Cooder|year=2011|format=CD booklet|publisher=Nonesuch Records|publisherid=527407|location=New York City}}</ref> Cooder also worked with vocalist [[Juliette Commagere]], accordionist [[Flaco Jim<U+00E9>nez]], bassist [[Robert Francis (musician)|Robert Francis]], vocalist [[Arnold McCuller]],<ref name="liner"/> and drummer Joachim Cooder, Cooder's son.<ref name="Jurek">{{cite web|last=Jurek|first=Thom|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/pull-up-some-dust-and-sit-down-r2224489/review|title=Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down - Ry Cooder|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation|at=Review|date=September 10, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> ''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'' was [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] by Martin Pradler and [[audio mastering|mastered]] by recording engineer [[Bernie Grundman]] at his Hollywood studio Grundman Mastering.<ref name="liner"/> Most of the album was engineered in Pradler's living room.<ref name="George">{{cite web|last=George|first=Lynell|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/ry-cooder-discusses-his-forthcoming-album-pull-up-some-dust-and-sit-down-2011-07-28|title=Ry Cooder Discusses His Forthcoming Album, "Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down"|publisher=Nonesuch Records|date=July 28, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref>

== Composition ==
=== Music and style ===
[[Image:Lehman Brothers Times Square by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|210px|The album was inspired by the late-2000s financial crisis. The collapse of the firm [[Lehman Brothers]] (headquarters pictured), a symbol of the crisis.]]
The album's music is rooted in [[Americana (music)|Americana]] and draws on styles such as [[blues]], [[folk music|folk]], [[ragtime]], [[norte<U+00F1>o (music)|norte<U+00F1>o]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[country music]].<ref name="Jurek"/> For the songs, Cooder adapted musical language from historical sources and incorporated styles from both North and South American traditions.<ref name="Paton"/><ref name="Chilton">{{cite web|last=Chilton|first=Martin|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/worldfolkandjazz/8739287/Ry-Cooder-Pull-Up-Some-Dust-And-Sit-Down-CD-review.html|title=Ry Cooder: Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down, CD review|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|date=September 3, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> In his interview on ''Marketplace'', he explained his stylistic approach for ''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'', stating "to me, these musical styles and sounds are narratives as well. I mean everything about them <U+2014> if it's an accordion, horns, the [[banda music|banda]] horns for the immigrant tunes <U+2014> they all are part of the story. And you can see it then, you can imagine the Arizona border that's hot, 120 degrees in the shade, dusty. The banda horns are coming from some truck over there."<ref name="Ryssdal"/> According to him, musical settings for certain songs were decided based on their respective compositions, such as when "the words would come to me in [[triple metre|<U+00BE> time]], that meant ''[[corrido]]'', that means accordion; ''banda'' horns because they<U+2019>re exciting."<ref name="George"/> 

Cooder wanted the music of each song to compliment the stories and to serve as homages to particular traditional styles.<ref name="George"/> Cooder said that he did not want to "over-think it" and said of his creative process for each song's distinct style, "It<U+2019>s taken a long time, but it becomes natural to combine an idea you have or a story you want to tell with whatever seems conducive."<ref name="George"/> Graham Reid of ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' writes that the music "refers to the dustbowl era, [[country blues|rural blues]], [[tejano music|Tex-Mex]] (with accordionist Flaco Jimenez) and old-time folk."<ref name="Reid">{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Graham|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=10750083|title=Album Review: Ry Cooder, Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down - Entertainment|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|publisher=[[APN News & Media]]|date=September 8, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> ''[[The Observer]]''{{'}}s Neil Spencer comments that it is "grounded in the blues, folk and Tex-Mex the guitarist explored in the 1970s, but its songs belong to modern times."<ref name="Spencer">{{cite web|last=Spencer|first=Neil|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2011/sep/04/pull-up-some-dust-review|title=Ry Cooder: Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down <U+2013> review <nowiki>|</nowiki> Music|work=[[The Observer]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|Guardian News and Media Limited]]|date=September 4, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref>

=== Lyrical themes ===
''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'' features [[political sociology|socio-political]] themes of power and its abuses, the struggle for [[democracy]], the trials of the [[working class]], and the goal of equality, with songs composed as either first-person narratives or allegories.<ref name="George"/><ref name="Schacht">{{cite web|last=Schacht|first=John|url=http://blurt-online.com/reviews/view/3358/|title=Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down by Ry Cooder|work=BLURT|date=October 3, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> The songs deal with contemporary subject matter and topics such as [[immigration law|immigration legislation]], the emotional and physical effects of war, the dubiousness of politics, [[social class]] and [[race (classification of humans)|race]] division, and [[white flight]].<ref name="George"/> Cooder's songwriting is characterized by sardonic lyrics, satire,<ref name="Houlihan">{{cite web|last=Houlihan|first=Mary|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/music/7769930-421/the-playlist-whats-in-the-earbuds-this-week.html|title=The Playlist: What<U+2019>s in the earbuds this week|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group|Sun-Times Media]]|date=September 22, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> mordant humor,<ref name="Cristiano">{{cite web|last=Cristiano|first=Nick|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/Ry_Cooder__Pull_Up_Some_Dust_and_Sit_Down.html|title=Ry Cooder, Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Holdings|Philadelphia Media Network]]|date=September 25, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> and wry observations on figures such as bankers, politicians, and militarists.<ref name="Horowitz">{{cite web|last=Horowitz|first=Hal|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2011/09/short-takes-ry-cooder-t-bone-burnetts-speaking-clock-revue-and-more/|title=Short Takes: Ry Cooder, T Bone Burnett<U+2019>s Speaking Clock Revue and More|work=[[American Songwriter]]|date=September 25, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> Nick Cristiano of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' writes of his lyrics, "Cooder takes deadly aim at rapacious bankers, warmongers, land barons, and the like, showing the devastating impact of their actions on ordinary folk", adding that "He does this in a manner that mixes the scrappy [[populism]] of Woody Guthrie with the first-person narratives of [[Bruce Springsteen|Springsteen]] in [[John Steinbeck|Steinbeckian]] ''[[The Ghost of Tom Joad|Ghost of Tom Joad]]'' mode."<ref name="Cristiano"/> Robin Denselow of ''[[The Guardian]]'' notes "bleak or thoughtful lyrics [set] against jaunty melodies" and "no elaborate narratives" in the songs, while interpreting the album's motif to be that of "a broken, divided society and [[economic inequality|the gap between rich and poor]], but with the anger matched against humour."<ref name="Denselow">{{cite web|last=Denselow|first=Robin|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2011/sep/01/ry-cooder-pull-up-review|title=Ry Cooder: Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down <U+2013> review <nowiki>|</nowiki> Music|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=September 1, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> [[Allmusic]]'s Steve Huey writes that the album "reache[s] all the way back to his earliest recordings for musical inspiration while telling topical stories about corruption <U+2014> political and social <U+2014> the erasure and the rewriting of [[history of the United States|American history]], and an emerging [[class conflict|class war]]."<ref name="Huey"/> 

Neil Spencer of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' calls the album "an impassioned portrait of 21st century America and its injustices", adding that "like Guthrie, [Cooder] nails his targets with droll humour while empathising with society's underdogs."<ref name="Nonesuch">{{cite web|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/hear-ry-cooder-new-album-entirety-slate-exclusive-5-stars-uncut-one-his-best-albums-ever-2011-08-24|title=Hear Ry Cooder's New Album in Its Entirety in Slate Exclusive; Five Stars from Uncut, "One of His Best Albums Ever"|publisher=Nonesuch Records|date=August 24, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> Allmusic's Thom Jurek characterizes it as "overtly political" and comments that "the depth of Cooder's rage is quieter but more direct as the album draws to a close."<ref name="Jurek"/> Peter Kane of ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' compares it to Cooder's 1971 studio album ''[[Into the Purple Valley]]'', which featured Dust Bowl-era songs, and writes that ''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down''{{'}}s "protest songs for today's messed-up world" are "sly and humorous".<ref name="Kane">{{cite journal|last=Kane|first=Peter|title=Ry Cooder, Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down (Nonesuch)|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|issue=303|page=117|month=October|year=2011}}</ref> On its themes, journalist [[Alec Wilkinson]] compares the album to Cooder's previous trilogy of Los Angeles-themed albums, which comprimised ''[[Ch<U+00E1>vez Ravine (album)|Ch<U+00E1>vez Ravine]]'' (2005), ''[[My Name Is Buddy]]'' (2007), and ''I, Flathead'' (2008).<ref name="Wilkinson">{{cite web|last=Wilkinson|first=Alec|url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2011/08/ry-cooder-pull-up-some-dust-and-sit-down.html|title=News Desk: Ry Cooder<U+2019>s Elegant Indignation|work=[[The New Yorker]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications|Cond<U+00E9> Nast]]|date=August 30, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> Wilkinson stated, "What {{'}}''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down''{{'}} shares with them is an indignation over the economic and ethical disparities of American life and the destructive and scoundrely meanness of the privileges given to the rich."<ref name="Wilkinson"/> Philip Majorins of [[PopMatters]] compares the album to other American songwriters' "substantial statements" about the American [[zeitgeist]], including [[Randy Newman]]'s ''[[Harps and Angels]]'' (2008), [[Paul Simon]]'s ''[[So Beautiful or So What]]'' (2011), and [[Bob Dylan]]'s ''[[Modern Times (Bob Dylan album)|Modern Times]]'' (2006).<ref name="Majorins">{{cite web|last=Majorins|first=Philip|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/149232-ry-cooder-pull-up-some-dust-and-sit-down/|title=Ry Cooder: Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|date=October 11, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-12}}</ref> However, Majorins distinguishes ''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'' as "an attempt at the existential, providing an everyman's view of struggle during economic downturn, class disparity, injustice, and abuse of power", and he calls Cooder "a direct voice of protest, both musically and lyrically, that will not be mistaken for being impressionistic."<ref name="Majorins"/>

== Content ==
{| style="font-size:100%" align="right" border="0" color="black" width=130px
| 
