|}
The opening track "No Banker Left Behind" references the financial bailout of 2007 and criticizes bankers and government.<ref name="Jurek"/><ref name="Houlihan"/> Alec Wilkinson of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' writes that the song "ridicules the considerations extended to the prosperous men and women who grabbed everything not nailed down during the last few years."<ref name="Wilkinson"/> It features [[march (music)|marching]] rhythms, [[mandolin]] and [[banjo]] riffs, and electric guitar.<ref name="Jurek"/> Cooder has described the song's rhythm as "a kind of [[clogging|clog-dance]] beat".<ref name="Ryssdal"/> "El Corrido Jesse James" is played in [[time signature|waltz time]] with a horn section and accordion by Flaco Jim<U+00E9>nez.<ref name="Jurek"/> The lyrics express a fictitious narrative by American outlaw Jessie James in [[Heaven]], who claims to have never "turned a family from their house" when he was a bank robber.<ref name="Jurek"/> He asks God for his "trusty [[.44 Magnum|.44]]" to persuade bankers to "put that bonus money back where it belongs".<ref name="Wilkinson"/> Cooder discussed the character's perspective in an interview on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'', stating "[T]he point here is that Jesse James was a primitive white man from the 19th Century. And in those days the hero was a one-man, one-gun hero. It's a very popular American myth. But what Jesse doesn't realise [in the song] is that while he's been up in heaven, the forces massed against him [...] He can't overcome the growth of the corporate, [[Military<U+2013>industrial complex|military-industrial equation]]. He can't walk down Wall Street and shoot up the place. No-one would even pay attention to him. The hero is outnumbered and outgunned. The wagons are circling, but what's he going to do? What's anyone going to do?"<ref name="Stanbridge">{{cite web|last=Stanbridge|first=Nicola|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-15037331|title=Ry Cooder takes on the bankers|work=''[[BBC News]]''|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=September 24, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> 

"Quick Sand" is a shuffling rock song that addresses the plight of illegal immigrants entering Arizona.<ref name="Jurek"/> It follows six migrants travelling through the extreme climate of the [[Sonoran Desert]] to reach [[U.S. Route 491|Devil's Highway]] in an attempt to cross the [[Mexico <U+2013> United States border]].<ref name="Quicksand"/><ref name="Stanbridge"/> They journey from [[Tamaulipas]] and through the mountains along Devil's Highway. Partway into the journey, the migrants are abandoned by their [[People smuggling#Coyotes|coyote guide]] and subsequently lose one another one by one.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lewis|first=Randy|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/07/ry-cooder-quicksand-immigration-arizona.html|title=Ry Cooder 'Quicksand' single targets Arizona's SB 1070 immigration law|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=July 1, 2010|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> They experience thirst, hunger, injury, and fear, culminating with the only two surviving migrants being turned away by a vigilante at the border.<ref name="Quicksand"/> Cooder said of the route's background and the narrative in an interview, "[I]t's been a migrant trail for 200 years. People go out there and try to do it on foot, but if you make one mistake and go five minutes out of your way, you become disorientated and dehydrated. And they find these mummified bodies out there. The heat has just baked them through. And the people who live through it often refer to having a vision of the [[Our Lady of Guadalupe|Virgin of Guadalupe]] flying overhead. This is a very common vision when the dehydration sets in."<ref name="Stanbridge"/> Featuring guitar flourishes and [[Nashville sound|countrypolitan]] strings,<ref name="Schacht"/> "Dirty Chateau" follows an exchange between a reckless rich man with a big house and his maid, who comes from a community of farm workers.<ref name="Wilkinson"/> 

"Humpty Dumpty World" incorporates the [[marimba]] with light [[reggae]] and [[Mariachi]] influences.<ref name="Paton"/><ref name="Gill">{{cite web|last=Gill|first=Andy|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-ry-cooder-pull-up-some-dust-and-sit-down-nonesuch-2347604.html|title=Album: Ry Cooder, Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down (Nonesuch) - Reviews, Music|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> The song's lyrics are sung from the perspective of God, who deplores the world He created.<ref name="Wilkinson"/> He makes note of incitive politicians and craven television commentators, and views it as "a ball of confusion" in the chorus line,<ref name="Houlihan"/> "I thought I had built upon a solid rock / But it<U+2019>s just a Humpty Dumpty World".<ref name="Wilkinson"/> "Christmas Time This Year" is an anti-war song with a Mexican [[polka]] style,<ref name="Jurek"/> with Flaco Jim<U+00E9>nez on accordion and Cooder on [[bajo sexto]].<ref name="liner"/> Composed as a corrido,<ref name="Christgau">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://social.entertainment.msn.com/music/blogs/expert-witness-blogpost.aspx?post=7c98cd46-3194-406a-ab8f-7cc2f70060ca|title=Ry Cooder/Note of Hope|work=''[[MSN Music]]''|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|date=September 27, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> the song is about wounded soldiers returning home for Christmas,<ref name="Fyfe">{{cite web|last=Fyfe|first=Andy|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/ff8r|title=Review of Ry Cooder - Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|work=''[[BBC Music]]''|publisher=BBC|date=August 30, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> with dismal lyrics set incongruously to an upbeat Mexican melody.<ref name="Chilton"/> Cooder wrote the song in response to the [[Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal]] and previous stories of neglected soldiers returning from the [[Iraq War]].<ref name="George"/> In "Baby Joined the Army", a young man laments the departure of his girlfriend, who became uninterested in her town and enlisted in the army with the assurance that "If I get killed in battle, I still get paid."<ref name="Wilkinson"/> "Lord Tell Me Why" is a [[gospel music|gospel]] song with a rolling [[funk]] [[groove (music)|groove]],<ref name="Jurek"/> sung from the perspective of a lower class White man who has become disillusioned with the [[American dream]].<ref name="Gill"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Shepherd|first=Fiona|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/Album-review-Ry-Cooder-Pull.6830718.jp|title=Album review: Ry Cooder, Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|work=[[The Scotsman]]|publisher=[[Johnston Press]]|date=September 6, 2011|accessdate=2010-10-01|archiveurl=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-29559876.html|archivedate=2011-12-10}}</ref> His ironic lyrics ask in the chorus, "Lord tell me why a white man / Ain't worth nothin' in this world no more."<ref name="Jurek"/> The guitar-based "I Want My Crown" was recorded with an 11-piece band and has an aggressive blues style,<ref name="Jurek"/> [[rumba]]-rock groove, and growling vocals.<ref name="Gill"/> The song is an indictment of politicians as "Judas men" who sided with oil barons and Republicans,<ref name="Gill"/> and their greed that leads to war.<ref name="Spencer"/> "I Want My Crown" has been described by one writer as a "[[Mephistopheles]]-as-[[right-wing politics|Right-winger]] character study".<ref name="Schacht"/>

"John Lee Hooker for President" is a blues song in which Cooder narrates as American blues musician [[John Lee Hooker]] visiting the [[White House]].<ref name="Ryssdal"/><ref name="Jurek"/> Adopting Hooker's style and laconic vocal tone, he decides to run for the presidency after disliking what he observed in his visit, naming [[Jimmy Reed]] as Vice President,<ref name="Jurek"/> [[Little Johnny Taylor]] as Secretary of State,<ref name="Houlihan"/> and proposing to have "nine fine-lookin' womens on the Supreme Court".<ref name="Cristiano"/> According to Cooder, the song was inspired by blues musician [[Gus Cannon]]'s 1927 song "Can You Blame the Colored Man", a satirical piece about [[Booker T. Washington]]'s [[Booker T. Washington#Up from Slavery.2C and an invitation to the White House|invitation to the White House]] by President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] in 1901.<ref name="Shedden"/> "Simple Tools" is a Tex-Mex ballad about the contentment of leading a simple lifestyle,<ref name="Fyfe"/> with references to the decline in traditional manual skills and the view of automated work as unfulfilling.<ref name="Staunton">{{cite web|last=Staunton|first=Terry|url=http://www.recordcollectormag.com/reviews/review-detail/7520|title=Ry Cooder - Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down <nowiki>|</nowiki> Album Review|work=[[Record Collector]]|publisher=Diamond Publishing|date=September 10, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> Featuring a resounding mix of mandolin and guitar,<ref name="Wilkinson"/> "If There Is a God" is a satirical narrative about an afterlife in which Heaven is restricted by a government bill to the wealthy.<ref name="Gill"/> Its lyrics criticize [[redistricting]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] legislature.<ref name="Jurek"/> The song references "[[The Bourgeois Blues]]" by blues and folk musician [[Lead Belly]].<ref name="Gill"/> In "No Hard Feelings", Cooder sings from the perspective of a lowly prospector who scolds businessmen for dealing with land exclusively in business terms.<ref name="Gill"/> He dismisses the rich and elite as "ripples" in history and is willing to tolerate them provided that they avoid conflict.<ref name="Fyfe"/>

== Release and promotion ==
The album was released by [[Nonesuch Records]] on August 30, 2011, in the United States.<ref name="Nonesuch"/> It was released in the United Kingdom on September 5,<ref name="Paton"/> and on September 9 in other European countries.<ref name="ATchart">{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Ry+Cooder&titel=Pull+Up+Some+Dust+And+Sit+Down&cat=a|title=Ry Cooder - Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|work=''austriancharts.at''|publisher=Hung Medien|language=German|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> Its [[LP record|vinyl LP]] release was on September 13.<ref name="Nonesuch"/> The album's [[lead single]], "Quicksand", was released as a [[music download|digital download]] on June 29, 2010.<ref name="Quicksand"/> Cooder donated the proceeds from its sales to the [[Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund]].<ref name="Quicksand"/> The single's cover artwork, a piece called ''Nuthin' to See Here, Keep on Movin'!'', was designed by visual artist Vincent Valdez, a frequent collaborator with Cooder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/ry-cooders-quicksand-response-arizona-immigration-law-available-itunes-proceeds-donated-maldef-2010-06-29|title=Ry Cooder's "Quicksand," Response to Arizona Immigration Law, Now Available on iTunes; Proceeds Donated to MALDEF|publisher=Nonesuch Records|date=June 29, 2010|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> Valdez contributed photography to the album's liner booklet.<ref name="liner"/> Cooder performed with a 17-piece band at the [[Great American Music Hall]] in San Francisco, California on August 31 and September 1.<ref name="Nonesuch"/> However, he was not satisfied with the shows' promotional aspect, and elaborated on it as part of his general disillusionment with the music industry in an interview for ''[[The Australian]]'', stating: 

{{quote|We had a 16-piece band and we played great shows to 700 people a night. But none of them bought CDs. None of them. They had a good time but they weren't motivated to buy CDs. I don't understand it because I came up in the time of records. Back then the business ran. You still got the tunes out. It was a crooked business, you could get cheated and there could be crooked accounting, but I still prefer it to this new thing where there is no connection to the audience through radio or retail.<ref name="Shedden"/>|Ry Cooder}}

== Reception ==
=== Commercial performance ===
The album debuted at number five on the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Folk Albums|Top Folk Albums]] chart in the week of September 24, 2011.<ref name="bbfolk">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/folk-albums?chartDate=2011-09-24|title=Folk Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media]]|at=Week of September 24, 2011|date=September 18, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> It charted at number 123 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and number 28 on the [[Billboard charts#Top Rock Albums|Top Rock Albums]].<ref name="bbcharts">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/pull-up-some-dust-and-sit-down-r2224489/charts-awards|title=Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down - Ry Cooder|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> The album also charted at number 15 on the ''Billboard'' [[Billboard charts#Albums|Tastemaker Albums]],<ref name="bbfolk"/> a chart that ranks top-selling albums "based on an influential panel of [[independent music|indie]] stores and small regional chains."<ref>{{cite web|last=Binkert|first=Lisa|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/events/bruno-mars-live-billboard-tastemakers-video-1004123318.story|title=Bruno Mars Live: Billboard Tastemakers Video|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|date=October 21, 2010|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref>

In the United Kingdom, ''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'' debuted at number 26 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], selling 6,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sexton|first=Paul|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/the-beatles-and-doris-day-crack-top-10-on-1005348562.story|title=The Beatles and Doris Day Crack Top 10 on U.K. Album Chart|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|date=September 12, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> It spent two weeks on the chart.<ref name="UKchart">{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/ry%20cooder/|title=Ry Cooder|publisher=The Official Charts Company|at=View Albums|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> In Belgium, the album debuted at number 31 on the [[Ultratop|Ultratop 50 Albums]]. It peaked at number 21 and spent four weeks on the chart.<ref name="BEchart">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Ry+Cooder&titel=Pull+Up+Some+Dust+And+Sit+Down&cat=a|title=Ry Cooder - Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|work=''[[Ultratop|ultratop.be]]''|publisher=ULTRATOP & Hung Medien / hitparade.ch|language=Dutch|accessdate-2011-10-05}}</ref> The album entered at number 24 and spent five weeks on the [[MegaCharts|Mega Album Top 100]] chart in the Netherlands.<ref name="NLchart">{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Ry+Cooder&titel=Pull+Up+Some+Dust+And+Sit+Down&cat=a|title=Ry Cooder - Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|work=''dutchcharts.nl''|publisher=Hung Medien / hitparade.ch|language=Dutch|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> In Norway, it debuted at number 13 on the [[VG-lista|VG-lista Top 40 Albums]]. It peaked at number nine and spent five weeks on the chart.<ref name="NOchart">{{cite web|url=http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Ry+Cooder&titel=Pull+Up+Some+Dust+And+Sit+Down&cat=a|title=Ry Cooder - Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down|work=''norwegiancharts.com''|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> In Ireland, the album reached number 26 and spent four weeks on the [[Irish Albums Chart]].<ref name="IRchart">{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/aucharts.asp|title=>> IRMA << Irish Charts - Singles, Albums & Compilations >>|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|date=September 29, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-05|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62DoaTLia|archivedate=2011-10-05}}</ref>

=== Critical response ===
{{Album ratings
| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]
| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="Jurek"/>
| rev2 = [[Robert Christgau]]
| rev2Score = (A<U+2013>)<ref name="Christgau"/>
| rev3 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''
| rev3Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name="Chilton"/>
| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''
| rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name="Denselow"/>
| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''
| rev5Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name="Gill"/>
| rev6 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''
| rev6Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="Sutcliffe"/>
| rev7 = ''[[The Observer]]''
| rev7Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name="Spencer"/>
| rev8 = [[PopMatters]]
| rev8Score = (8/10)<ref name="Majorins"/>
| rev9 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''
| rev9Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="Kane"/>
| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''
| rev10Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name="Williamson"/>
}}
''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'' received general acclaim from [[music criticism|music critic]]s.<ref name="Metacritic">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/pull-up-some-dust-and-sit-down|title=Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More at Metacritic|work=''[[Metacritic]]''|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[weighted mean]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 92, based on 14 reviews, which indicates "universal acclaim".<ref name="Metacritic"/> [[Allmusic]] editor Thom Jurek gave it four out of five stars and cited it as "the most overtly political album Ry Cooder has ever released, and one of his funniest, most musically compelling ones, too."<ref name="Jurek"/> [[MusicOMH]]'s Daniel Paton complimented Cooder's incorporation of traditional musical styles and stated, "For the most part, ''Pull Up Some Dust...'' is highly satisfying satire (although also often sensitive and affecting), combining Cooder<U+2019>s transparent love for a wide range of [[American folk music|roots music]] with his engagement with politics."<ref name="Paton"/> Martin Chilton of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' praised its songs as "stunning" and dubbed it "one of the best albums of a distinguished career."<ref name="Chilton"/> Hal Horowitz of ''[[American Songwriter]]'' commented that Cooder's "working class messages are enhanced by sharp musical chops".<ref name="Horowitz"/> Terry Staunton of ''[[Record Collector]]'' called the album "thought-provoking at every turn and elegantly wrapped in a dizzying array of musically schizophrenic paper" and commended Cooder's "keen observational eye", stating "Cooder's deft grip on American vernacular music infuses what could be a pretty sombre journey with some dazzling jumps in style."<ref name="Staunton"/> 

''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' writer Mary Houlihan gave the album three-and-a-half out of four stars, calling it "an album that matters" and Cooder "a modern-day Woody Guthrie".<ref name="Houlihan"/> Phil Sutcliffe of ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' complimented Cooder's own musical influences and "trenchant commentary", noting "the spirit of Woody Guthrie".<ref name="Sutcliffe">{{cite journal|last=Sutcliffe|first=Phil|title=Ry Cooder, Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down (Nonesuch)|work=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|publisher=Bauer Media Group|issue=96|page=215|month=October|year=2011}}</ref> ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]''{{'}}s Graham Reid gave the album a five out of five rating and praised Cooder's "old styles and politics".<ref name="Reid"/> Neil Spencer of ''[[The Observer]]'' described it as "a fierce state-of-the-nation album" and called Cooder "a Woody Guthrie for our times."<ref name="Spencer"/> Robin Denselow of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the album "magnificent" and "as refreshing, brave and original as his early recordings in the 70s."<ref name="Denselow"/> Andy Gill of ''[[The Independent]]'' dubbed it "his best effort by far since ''[[Ch<U+00E1>vez Ravine (album)|Chavez Ravine]]''" and perceived "a dark parade of familiar Cooder figures [...] But almost everywhere one looks, Cooder finds a new twist on these old rivalries."<ref name="Gill"/> [[Nigel Williamson]] of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' gave it five out of five stars and dubbed it "one of his best albums ever".<ref name="Williamson">{{cite journal|last=Williamson|first=Nigel|authorlink=Nigel Williamson|title=Ry Cooder, Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down (Nonesuch)|journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|issue=173|page=83|month=October|year=2011}}</ref> [[BBC Music]]'s Andy Fyfe commented that "this is about as good and sustained a [[wikt:riposte|riposte]] to the grubby, grabbing times we live in as any artist has mustered, which makes it essential listening."<ref name="Fyfe"/> 

In his consumer guide for [[MSN Music]], critic [[Robert Christgau]] gave the album an A<U+2013> rating,<ref name="Christgau"/> indicating "the kind of garden-variety good record that is the great luxury of musical micromarketing and overproduction."<ref>{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bk-cg90/grades-90s.php|title=CG 90s: Key to Icons|publisher=Robert Christgau|date=October 15, 2000|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref> Christgau commented that "Cooder has brought his longstanding obsession with the Great Depression into the present, where it unfortunately, tragically, enragingly belongs", adding that the album "doesn't rock, and it shouldn't. But it rollicks, skanks, and two-steps just fine."<ref name="Christgau"/> Philip Majorins of [[PopMatters]] commented that the album "may not be a seamless narrative, but the themes are clear. Ry Cooder plays the part of the prophet flawlessly".<ref name="Majorins"/> Majorins added that it would not have a significant impact due to commercial tastes and a "cynical" cultural climate, but wrote in conclusion, "''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'' could have tremendous cathartic power for [those] who are aware of history and its knack for repeating itself. For those who are willing, this is a good place to start an education."<ref name="Majorins"/> Peter Kane of ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' gave the album four out of five stars and described its music as "the heartening sounds of an old master at work."<ref name="Kane"/>

=== Accolades ===
''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' ranked the album number 20 on its list of Top 50 Albums of 2011.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Staff|title=Top 50 Albums of 2011|journal=Uncut|publisher=IPC Media|issue=176|month=January|year=2011}}</ref> ''Pull Up Some Dust and Sit Down'' was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]], set to be presented at the [[54th Grammy Awards]] in 2012.<ref name="Grammy">{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees|title=Nominees and Winners|work=''[[Grammy Awards|GRAMMY]]''|publisher=[[The Recording Academy]]|accessdate=2011-12-01|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63bEmKvH7|archivedate=2011-12-01}}</ref>

